sols_latex:
From the eigenvalue decomposition

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
A^TA = V\Sigma^2V^{-1}
\end{align*}

we see that the eigenvalues of \emph{A\textsuperscript{T}A} are the
squares of the diagonal entries in $\displaystyle \Sigma$, that is

\begin{align*}
\lambda_{1}=4, \quad \lambda_{2}=1, \quad \lambda_{3}=\frac{1}{4}
\end{align*}

Further, the corresponding eigenvectors of \emph{A\textsuperscript{T}A}
are the column vectors of \emph{V}, namely

\begin{align*}
\vec{v_{1}}=\begin{bmatrix}
\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\\
\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\\
\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}
\end{bmatrix}
, \quad \vec{v_{2}}=\begin{bmatrix}
0\\
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\\
-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}
\end{bmatrix}
, \quad \vec{v_{3}}=\begin{bmatrix}
\frac{2}{\sqrt{6}}\\
-\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}\\
-\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

